Quality of the resting-state fMRI

Physiological measures were acquired with a breathing belt and pulse oximetry. Preprocessing was done with the Physio Toolbox in Matlab (see physio preprocessing and PhysiO-toolbox). A rough check for completeness of physiological recordings was checked based on file size. See script check_filesize

Physiological parameters extracted with the Physio Toolbox were the resampled respiratory and PPU traces (raw recordings downsampled to fMRI resolution), heart and cardiac phase and heart rate (HR) and respiratory volume per time (RVT)

both erroneous 3

Head motion was assessed with mean and maximal framewise displacement based on motion parameters from MCFLIRT (Power, 2012). Previous and current methods to calculate mean FD agree:

In addition, DVARS (D referring to temporal derivative of timecourses, VARS referring to RMS variance over voxels) was calculated nipype/ComputeDvars. DVARS is a measure of how much the intensity of a brain image changes in comparison to the previous timepoint (as opposed to the global signal, which is the average value of a brain image at a timepoint).

Association of motion parameters and physio parameters in the followup (N= 239)

Distribution of motion parameters and DVARS

Strong correlation of mean FD and DVARS

Low/no correlation of motion/DVARS and downsampled resp./PPI traces

Low/moderate correlation of mean FD and derived physiological parameters RVT and HR

Low/moderate correlation of DVARS and derived physiological parameters RVT and HR

So differences in heart rate and respiratory volume explain only small amount of variance in motion and BOLD fluctuations. Yet, head motion and BOLD fluctuations are strongly associated.

Still, the impact of physiological parameters might be stronger in high motion subjects. There are 20 participants with mean FD > 0.5 mm or max FD > 3mm in the followup sample. 189 have a mean FD > 0.2 mm.

The association of RVT and DVARS is not more pronounced in participants who move more. (Here it was hypothesized that they would breathe possibly more heavily)

Head motion compared with baseline assessment

Cross-sectional analysis

At baseline and followup, head motion and BMI were strongly associated, even when correcting for age and sex (anova comparison of null model (age,sex) with BMI model (age,sex,BMI) of mean FD: baseline: F=35.22, p=1.136187110^{-8}, followup: F=57.1, p=1.101816810^{-12}). The BMI coefficients are very comparable, but there is less motion in the followup.

Longitudinal analysis

Participants move less at the followup compared to the baseline assessment (possibly due to training, less nervousness or better head positioning). When comparing baseline and followup, Chisq-test was significant (Chisq=37.69, p=8.287070510^{-10}).

Is the association of BMI and head motion due to stronger breathing?

Then the association of DVARS and RVT/HR should be stronger in people with higher BMI (as for these people higher stronger breathing should explain more variance in DVARS)

BMI does not predict higher correlation of DVARS and RVT/HR. Age is weakly associated with corr_dvars_RV (p=0.08). Generally, the variance explained by demographic factors in measures reflecting the correlation of physiological markers and head motion/DVARS is very low (<1%).
